My husband and I planned an engagement party in D.C. to be held at the Riggsby Restaurant at the Kimpton Carlyle Hotel, from long-distance in North Carolina. Research between other options led us to the Riggsby’s Fitzgerald Room. Events Coordinator, Stenise, walked me through final plans for our dinner party, from start to finish, on the telephone, and confirmed on email.She assured me that from the moment our guests arrived, our event would be taken care of and handled with the utmost care and finesse.  The day of our event, the GM, Adam and our head waiter, Kareem, assured us that we would be cared for and receive exceptional food, drink and service. The Fitzgerald Room was perfect for our twelve guests, with the candlelit table and background music. Kareem ‘s personality lit up the room, and the wine and food selections were beautiful as well as delectable.  Everyone involved in the planning and execution of the evening are owed our heartfelt thanks. Not only was the evening special, the staff and location provided a lifetime of memories, not only for the engaged couple, but their parents and guests as well!  Five Stars!!!

The Riggsby is a lovely restaurant located in the Carlyle Hotel in Washington, D.C. With its wood paneled walls and leather chairs, it harks back to an earlier era. The brunch menu, for example, includes duck confit hash. It's great, but is a far cry from corned beef hash!  Servers are friendly and efficient without intruding inappropriately upon conversation. They keep an attentive eye open for a customer's look or gesture and are quick to respond.  Prices are mid range, but not prohibitive. All in all, it is a delightful place to meet and share a meal with friends.

The food here is outstanding and the service is excellent.  Several things about it are quirky, from the waiters that walk around just to put a piece of bread on your bread plate to a coat-check style take-home box system where they give you a ticket for your box.  My wife and I went with friends and tried a couple appetizers.  I am not the biggest seafood person outside of some basic things like shrimp, salmon, and crab, but the calamari here was really excellent!  I ordered the pork chop which was one of the best I have ever had.  It comes pre-sliced, though you will cut it up more, and then smothered in a great European-type sauce that includes spicy sausage, potatoes, onions, fresh garlic, and other ingredients.  It is spicy as were several other dishes.  My wife ordered the roasted chicken which I thought was cooked incredibly well and just outstanding.  A friend ordered the bronzino, which was a wonderful, smaller plate with a great green sauce and a well cooked piece of fish.  We save a little bit of room for dessert and no one could decide between three desserts, so the four of us ordered (though we failed to finish) all three--a brownie bottom sunday pie, rhubarb pie, and banana pudding.  I can be weird about creamy textures and am not a pudding fan, but the banana pudding was incredible.  I could go back just for it.  The strawberry rhubarb pie was outstanding and gave me a nostalgic feeling for home, down South.  The brownie sunday thing was really great, but so big and intense that you couldn't really get through all of it.  It was stacked so high you almost had no hope of getting ice-cream and the very-much buried brownie in one bite.  We were all very impressed as the just how good all of the desserts were--three swings and three hits!  On a final note, we all ordered drinks as well and the old fashioned there was just outstanding.  It was one of the best, top two, for old fashioned's I've had in the District.  Our waiter was also phenomenal--very attentive and great with a group that was prone to talking to him.  This place is expensive, but very much worth it.  I would go back for a special dinner, date-night, or a special occasion.  They seemed to be able to deal very well with bigger tables of people.  Hopefully this review will associate with the pictures I previously posted so you can see some of the items we had.
